Then
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n} \cdot (\mathbf{p} \times \mathbf{m}) &= \mathbf{n} \cdot (a \mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{m} + b \mathbf{n} \times \mathbf{m}) \\
&= \mathbf{n} \cdot (a \mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{m} + b (\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}) \times \mathbf{m}) \\
&= \mathbf{n} \cdot (a \mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{m} + b (\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{m}) \mathbf{m} - b (\mathbf{m} \cdot \mathbf{m}) \mathbf{n}) \\
&= \mathbf{n} \cdot (a \mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{m} - b \mathbf{m}) \\
&= -b \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{m} \\
&= -b \cos \alpha.
\end{align*}Hence, $-b \cos \alpha = \frac{1}{4},$ so $b = -\frac{1}{4 \cos \alpha}.$  Then
\[\mathbf{p} = a \mathbf{m} - \frac{1}{4 \cos \alpha} \mathbf{n}.\]Since $\mathbf{p}$ is a unit vector,
\[|\mathbf{p}|^2 = a^2 + \frac{1}{16 \cos^2 \alpha} = 1.\]Then $a^2 = 1 - \frac{1}{16 \cos^2 \alpha} = \frac{16 \cos^2 \alpha - 1}{16 \cos^2 \alpha}.$

Also, $\mathbf{m} \cdot \mathbf{n} = \cos \alpha,$ so
\[\cos \alpha = \mathbf{m} \cdot \mathbf{n} = (\mathbf{m} \cdot \mathbf{p}) - (\mathbf{m} \cdot \frac{1}{4 \cos \alpha} \mathbf{n}) = a \mathbf{m} \cdot \mathbf{m} - \frac{1}{4} = a - \frac{1}{4}.\]Then $a = \cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}.$

Hence,
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{p} &= (\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{m} - \frac{1}{4 \cos \alpha} \mathbf{n} \\
&= (\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{m} - \frac{\sin \alpha}{4} \mathbf{n} \cot \alpha \\
&= (\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{m} - \frac{\sin \alpha}{4} \mathbf{n} \frac{\cos \alpha}{\sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \alpha}} \\
&= (\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{m} - \frac{\sin \alpha}{4} \frac{\cos \alpha}{\sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \alpha}} \mathbf{n}.
\end{align*}We want the angle between $\mathbf{p}$ and $\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}$ to be $\alpha,$ which means
\[\frac{(\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}) \cdot \mathbf{p}}{\|\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}\| \|\mathbf{p}\|} = \cos \alpha.\]Since $\mathbf{m}$ and $\mathbf{n}$ are unit vectors,
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}) \cdot \mathbf{p} &= \mathbf{m} \cdot (\mathbf{n} \times \mathbf{p}) \\
&= \mathbf{m} \cdot (\mathbf{n} \times ((\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{m} - \frac{\sin \alpha}{4} \frac{\cos \alpha}{\sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \alpha}} \mathbf{n})) \\
&= \mathbf{m} \cdot ((\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{n} \times \mathbf{m} - \frac{\sin \alpha}{4} \frac{\cos \alpha}{\sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \alpha}} \mathbf{n} \times \mathbf{n}) \\
&= \mathbf{m} \cdot ((\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{n} \times \mathbf{m}) \\
&= (\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \mathbf{m} \cdot (\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}) \\
&= (\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \|\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}\|.
\end{align*}Also,
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{p}\| &= \sqrt{(\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4})^2 + \frac{\sin^2 \alpha \cos^2 \alpha}{16(1 - \cos^2 \alpha)}} \\
&= \frac{1}{4} \sqrt{16 \cos^2 \alpha - 8 \cos \alpha + 17}.
\end{align*}Therefore,
\[\cos \alpha = \frac{(\cos \alpha + \frac{1}{4}) \|\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}\|}{\|\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n}\| \cdot \|\mathbf{p}\|} = \frac{4 \cos \alpha + 1}{\sqrt{16 \cos^2 \alpha - 8 \cos \alpha + 17}}.\]Then $4 \cos^2 \alpha - 2 \cos \alpha + 4 = 16 \cos^2 \alpha - 8 \cos \alpha + 17,$ so $15 \cos^2 \alpha - 6 \cos \alpha - 13 = 0.$  This factors as $(3 \cos \alpha + 1)(5 \cos \alpha - 13) = 0,$ so $\cos \alpha = \frac{-1}{3}$ or $\cos \alpha = \frac{13}{5}.$

If $\cos \alpha = \frac{-1}{3},$ then $\mathbf{p} = (\frac{-2}{3}, \frac{1}{3} \sqrt{\frac{10}{3}}, \frac{1}{3} \sqrt{\frac{10}{3}})$ and $\mathbf{m} \times \mathbf{n} = (-\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}, 0, \sqrt{\frac{1}{3}}).$  Then
\[\cos \alpha = \frac{\mathbf{m} \cdot \mathbf{n}}{\|\mathbf{m}\| \|\mathbf{n}\|} = \frac{0}{1} = 0,\]contradiction.

Therefore, $\cos \alpha = \frac{13}{5},$ and $\alpha = \boxed{\cos^{-1} \frac{13}{5}}.$
